04112nam a22005415i 9780300160529DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t19871987ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001605297 a10.12987/97803001605292doi  a(DE-B1597)486636  a(OCoLC)1024022549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDS135.G3315bB38 1994eb 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a940.53/18/09432221 aBeller, Andrea H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJews for Sale? /cAndrea H. Beller, John W. Graham. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[1987] 4c©1987  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world has recently learned of Oskar Schindler's efforts to save the lives of Jewish workers in his factory in Poland by bribing Nazi officials. Not as well known, however, are many other equally dramatic attempts to negotiate with the Nazis for the release of Jews in exchange for money, goods, or political benefits. In this riveting book, a leading Holocaust scholar examines these attempts, describing the cast of characters, the motives of the participants, the frustrations and few successes, and the moral issues raised by the negotiations.Drawing on a wealth of previously unexamined sources, Yehuda Bauer deals with the fact that before the war Hitler himself was willing to permit the total emigration of Jews from Germany in order to be rid of them. In the end, however, there were not enough funds for the Jews to buy their way out, there was no welcome for them abroad, and there was too little time before war began. Bauer then concentrates on the negotiations that took place between 1942 and 1945 as Himmler tried to keep open options for a separate peace with the Western powers.In fascinating detail Bauer portrays the dramatic intrigues that took place: a group of Jewish leaders bribed a Nazi official to stop the deportation of Slovakian Jews; a Czech Jew known as Dogwood tried to create an alliance between American leaders and conservative German anti-Nazis; Adolf Eichmann's famous "trucks for blood" proposal to exchange one million Jews for trucks to use against the Soviets failed because of Western reluctance; and much more.Tormenting questions arise throughout Bauer's discussion. If the Nazis were actually willing to surrender more Jews, should the Allies have acted on the offer? Did the efforts to exchange lives for money constitute collaboration with the enemy or heroism? In answering these questions, Bauer's book—engrossing, profound, and deeply moving—adds a new dimension to Holocaust studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zGermany. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1933-1945. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewsxRescuezGermany. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aGraham, John W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016052940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300160529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300160529/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles